1. Functional Interfaces (Deeper)

A lambda works only with a functional interface (one abstract method).

👉 Example:

@FunctionalInterface
interface MyFunction {
    int apply(int a, int b);
}

Using lambda:

MyFunction sum = (a, b) -> a + b;
2. Built-in Functional Interfaces

Java provides ready-to-use interfaces:

Predicate (returns boolean)
Predicate<Integer> isEven = x -> x % 2 == 0;
Function (takes input, returns result)
Function<Integer, String> convert = x -> "Number: " + x;
Consumer (takes input, returns nothing)
Consumer<String> print = x -> System.out.println(x);
Supplier (no input, returns value)
Supplier<Double> random = () -> Math.random();
3. Variable Capture (Important)

Lambdas can use variables from outside, but:

👉 they must be final or effectively final

int x = 10;

Runnable r = () -> {
    System.out.println(x);
};

❌ Not allowed:

int x = 10;
x = 20; // change

Runnable r = () -> System.out.println(x); // error
4. Lambda and “this”

👉 In lambda:

this refers to the outer class, not lambda itself

This is different from anonymous classes.

5. Method References (Cleaner Lambda)

Instead of:

list.forEach(x -> System.out.println(x));

You can write:

list.forEach(System.out::println);

👉 This is called method reference

Types of Method References
Class::staticMethod
object::instanceMethod
Class::new
6. Lambdas with Collections
Filtering
list.removeIf(x -> x.startsWith("A"));
Sorting
list.sort((a, b) -> a.compareTo(b));
forEach
list.forEach(x -> System.out.println(x));
7. Common Mistakes

❌ Trying to use lambda without functional interface
❌ Modifying captured variables
❌ Writing too complex lambdas (hard to read)

8. When NOT to use Lambda
complex logic → use normal methods
multiple responsibilities
when readability suffers
Summary
lambda works with functional interfaces
can capture effectively final variables
supports method references
widely used with collections
improves readability (if used correctly)
